<h2 class="pen"><a rel="bookmark" https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?id=737" title="Permanent link to this article">Madison Chautauqua Festival of Art</a></h2>

<div class="post">

<div class="entrytext">

	<p><a href="http://www.madisonchautauqua.com/">Madison Chautauqua Festival of Art</a></p>

	<p>The website&#8217;s not that great, but the weekend is. More than 200 artists attract 50,000 to 70,000 people to town over the weekend.</p>

	<p>The show doesn&#8217;t start until tomorrow, but already the streets are filling up. I hesitate to move the van until I absolutely have to for fear of losing the space until Sunday night.</p>

	<p>Every morning, I roll my bike out the front door on my way to work and whip around the corner as I mount. Since I bought my bike in mid-July, I have never seen anyone as I round the corner. This morning of course I nearly hit an elderly couple. CRINGE. I need to remember these things.</p>

	<p>In general, the show is really nice and features good art. However, compared to a few years ago, the quality of work is going down. It used to be gallery quality, but they have let in more country crafts. Not bad stuff, just not the stuff that will attract the upper-end clientel our town could thrive off of.</p>

	<p>Sometimes I just don&#8217;t think the people who live here &#8220;get it&#8221; and see what a gem this place is. They&#8217;re still in the mode of cheap antique shoppers. We can attract a lot better clientel than that. Indeed, we need to in order to keep the businesses on Main Street healthy in the long run.</p>

	<p>It&#8217;s hurting right now because tourism is down and the money to market tourism comes from tourism (hotel taxes) so the situation could just get worse.</p>

	<p>The flip of this equation is that people from Chicago, Key West and LA are discovering us and buying up property. We&#8217;re not paying attention to this trend either. We need to insure a means of keeping affordable housing, espcially in the downtown historic district.</p>

	<p>It&#8217;s all a balance.</p>

	<p>One woman from Bloomington bought a small little brick house. More cottage than house really. She calls it her &#8220;menopause home.&#8221; She paid more than $70,000 for it. For as small as the place was, that seems really high to me. Mind you the location was awesome, just across from the <a href="http://www.laniermansion.org/">Lanier Mansion</a>, and the condition was decent.</p>

	<p>I guess the kicker is that I make &#8220;Madison&#8221; wages and can&#8217;t afford it. She make &#8220;Bloomington&#8221; wages and can. Expensive here is cheap elsewhere.</p>

	<p>Again, it&#8217;s all a balance.</p>

	<p>OK, I&#8217;m off my soapbox for the afternoon.</p>



 

<p class="postmetadata alt">

